## This is forecast 6.2
library(tseries)

data_path <- "time-series.csv"
data <- read.csv(data_path, header = TRUE, sep = '\t')
dat1_ts <- ts(data$Dat1)
hist(data$Dat1, main = "Histogram for Data 1")

Looks like random data (white noise) with no trend

plot(dat1_ts, main = "Data 1 time series")

No peaks in autocorrelation function (ACF) partial autocorrelation function (PACF) suggest that data does not depend on previous observations (stationary time series)

tsdisplay(data$Dat1)

p-value for Dickey-Fuller suggest stationarity of the data

adf.test(data$Dat1, alternative = c("stationary"))
## Warning in adf.test(data$Dat1, alternative = c("stationary")): p-value
## smaller than printed p-value
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  data$Dat1
## Dickey-Fuller = -12.744, Lag order = 12, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

KPSS Test

kpss.test(data$Dat1)
## Warning in kpss.test(data$Dat1): p-value greater than printed p-value
## 
##  KPSS Test for Level Stationarity
## 
## data:  data$Dat1
## KPSS Level = 0.17265, Truncation lag parameter = 10, p-value = 0.1

Auto ARIMA selects ARIMA(0,0,0) model: 0 for ACF, PACF and 0 diffetials needed to make data stationary.

dat1_mod_a <- auto.arima(dat1_ts)
summary(dat1_mod_a)
## Series: dat1_ts

## Training set 0.02778337

Forecast selects just expected value and adds margin confidence and prediction intervals

forecast_1a <- forecast(dat1_mod_a, 200)
plot(forecast_1a)

From observations to observations growth for each next point (treating data as non stationary and trying to make it so for prediction)

dat1_diff <- diff(data$Dat1)

Looks like previous value has effect in ACF and few previous values are valid for PACF

tsdisplay(dat1_diff)

But coefficients for args are not significant (division < 1)

dat1_diff_ts <- ts(dat1_diff)
dat1_diff_mod_a <- auto.arima(dat1_diff_ts)
## Warning in auto.arima(dat1_diff_ts): Unable to fit final model using
## maximum likelihood. AIC value approximated
summary(dat1_diff_mod_a)

Slowly decaying ACF suggests that data is not stationary Clear positive trend is visible

hist(data$Dat2)

#non-stationar data with trend, random walk
tsdisplay(data$Dat2)

dat2 <- data$Dat2

First diff order to make data stationary

dat2_diff <- diff(dat2)

Time series plot suggest stationarity. ACF and PACF show that value depends on previous values.

tsdisplay(dat2_diff)

Stationarity hypothesis is rejected by Kwiatkowski-Phillips-Schmidt-Shin test

dat2_ts <- ts(dat2)
adf.test(dat2, alternative = c("stationary"))
## Warning in adf.test(dat2, alternative = c("stationary")): p-value smaller
## than printed p-value
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  dat2
## Dickey-Fuller = -6.5629, Lag order = 12, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
kpss.test(dat2)
## Warning in kpss.test(dat2): p-value smaller than printed p-value
## 
##  KPSS Test for Level Stationarity
## 
## data:  dat2
## KPSS Level = 13.861, Truncation lag parameter = 10, p-value = 0.01

Auto ARIMA selects (1,1,2) model. Drift coef 1 suggests that diff was required. All coef non zero - they are significant, drift 0.0138 suggests removed positive trend

dat2_mod_a <- auto.arima(dat2_ts)
summary(dat2_mod_a)

Forecast for 100 values shows future positive trend

forecast_2a <- forecast(dat2_mod_a, 100)
plot(forecast_2a)

Same for neural networks prediction

nn_fit <- nnetar(dat2)
